<!-- SC_OFF --><div class="md"><p>For me it&#39;s (very piano-biased, I know)</p> <p>-Schumann Gesaenge der Fruehe- Beautiful work which seems to inspire a minimum standard of playing from anyone who interprets it</p> <p>-Chopin F minor concerto (odd, as I hear plenty of bad recordings of the E minor concerto, but the F minor just seems way easier to interpret right)</p> <p>-Chopin Barcarolle- it&#39;s just so beautiful it&#39;s resistant to most bad handling</p> </div><!-- SC_ON --> &#32; submitted by &#32; <a href="https://www.reddit.com/user/opus52"> /u/opus52 </a> <br/> <span><a href="https://www.reddit.com/r/classicalmusic/comments/130y1hy/what_are_pieces_you_rarely_hear_bad_recordings_of/">[link]</a></span> &#32; <span><a href="https://www.reddit.com/r/classicalmusic/comments/130y1hy/what_are_pieces_you_rarely_hear_bad_recordings_of/">[comments]</a></span>